00:10:39,055 --> 00:10:42,224
at the 2002 Chili's Pro-Am in Orlando,

237
00:10:42,308 --> 00:10:44,518
"Suck on this drive, buttmunch!"

238
00:10:49,106 --> 00:10:50,733
Whoo!

239
00:10:50,816 --> 00:10:53,361
Nailed it.
That was a flusher but she sank.

240
00:10:53,444 --> 00:10:56,530
Perhaps an adept linksman
like yourself should play

241
00:10:56,614 --> 00:10:58,949
with the assistance filter turned off?

242
00:10:59,533 --> 00:11:02,578
-Let's play old-school.
-All right. Why not?

243
00:11:06,082 --> 00:11:08,125
Fork! You sneezed, man.

244
00:11:08,209 --> 00:11:10,836
I don't think I sneezed,
because I literally can't.

245
00:11:10,920 --> 00:11:12,755
Well, somebody sneezed. Damn it.

246
00:11:12,838 --> 00:11:15,132
Brent, buddy, nobody sneezed.

247
00:11:15,216 --> 00:11:18,803
-You hit a bad shot, and it's fine.
-[sighs]

248
00:11:18,886 --> 00:11:22,014
You know, it isn't a sign of weakness
to admit that you screwed up.

249
00:11:22,765 --> 00:11:24,266
Fine, whatever, I shanked it.

250
00:11:24,350 --> 00:11:29,688
There ya go. Now let's go find your ball,
and try to do better on your next shot.

251
00:11:29,772 --> 00:11:31,732
And you know, if this ends up

252
00:11:31,816 --> 00:11:36,946
applying to any other aspect
of your life later on, then cool.

253
00:11:37,780 --> 00:11:39,907
-What?
-What? Nothing. Nothing.

254
00:11:39,990 --> 00:11:41,534
[Michael] <i>I gotta say, Bad Janet,</i>

255
00:11:41,617 --> 00:11:44,662
I really felt like
I had managed to stop the bleeding.

256
00:11:44,745 --> 00:11:46,997
You thought that dingdong would do
a total personality 180

257
00:11:47,081 --> 00:11:48,958
because of one gentle metaphor?

258
00:11:49,041 --> 00:11:51,001
What can I say? I'm an optimist.

259
00:11:51,085 --> 00:11:55,464
{\an8}But two days later, at the event,
it fell apart almost immediately.

260
00:11:55,548 --> 00:11:58,050
{\an8}Hey, uh, thanks for not telling anyone
about Jason.

261
00:11:58,134 --> 00:12:01,804
Oh, well, ever since I arrived here,
Tahani helped me realize

262
00:12:01,887 --> 00:12:05,057
that gossip was an unhealthy way for me
to boost my self-esteem.

263
00:12:05,141 --> 00:12:08,561
But on the other hand,
this Jason tea needs to be spilled. [sobs]

264
00:12:08,644 --> 00:12:10,312
Just try to remember
what Immanuel Kant said,

265
00:12:10,396 --> 00:12:12,940
"It is your duty
to keep your friend's secrets."

266
00:12:13,023 --> 00:12:15,693
But my favorite philosopher,
Bethenny Frankel, would say

267
00:12:15,776 --> 00:12:20,114
that I have a duty to "mention it all!"
And "if you can't handle the truth,

268
00:12:20,197 --> 00:12:21,991
then you can't handle me."

269
00:12:22,074 --> 00:12:23,409
-[sighs]
-Once again, I beg you, please listen

270
00:12:23,492 --> 00:12:26,662
to Immanuel Kant and not Bethenny Frankel.

271
00:12:26,745 --> 00:12:29,123
Gah! Well, I gotta goss about something.

272
00:12:29,206 --> 00:12:30,207
What about a few blind items

273
00:12:30,291 --> 00:12:31,834
-that I picked up around the neighborhood?
-[sighs]

274
00:12:31,917 --> 00:12:33,794
You wanna know who wears
the same dumb shorts every day?

275
00:12:33,878 --> 00:12:36,005
-No, I don't.
-It's "Dumb Shorts Cathy."

276
00:12:36,755 --> 00:12:37,590
Simone?

277
00:12:38,466 --> 00:12:42,678
Uh, I have been thinking about those
very good questions that you asked me.

278
00:12:42,761 --> 00:12:43,888
I'm sorry for the delay.

279
00:12:43,971 --> 00:12:49,560
The ancient scrolls I had to consult
were very hard to... roll back up.

280
00:12:49,643 --> 00:12:53,022
Um, anyway, I thought about
what you should say to Brent

281
00:12:53,105 --> 00:12:54,899
when he asks
for your opinion of his novel.

282
00:12:54,982 --> 00:12:58,235
Me, too. I have a great idea.
I'm gonna tell him it sucks very hard.

283
00:12:58,319 --> 00:13:02,406
Well, listen. You're absolutely right
that Brent needs to evolve, but

284
00:13:02,490 --> 00:13:07,203
there may be a more subtle way
to make that happen.

285
00:13:07,786 --> 00:13:09,121
[Brent chuckles] Hey, there they are.

286
00:13:09,205 --> 00:13:11,332
-Charlie's Angels. [chuckles]
-[softly] Oof.

287
00:13:11,415 --> 00:13:13,250
So, did you finish the book?
What'd you think?

288
00:13:13,334 --> 00:13:17,129
Well, very interesting word choices.

289
00:13:17,213 --> 00:13:21,634
I've definitely never seen the word
"pants-tent" used so many times.

290
00:13:21,717 --> 00:13:23,385
Yeah. I kinda just felt like,
in that moment,

291
00:13:23,469 --> 00:13:25,554
that that's what the surgeon general
would say.

292
00:13:25,638 --> 00:13:27,640
What else? Let's hear some more complos.

293
00:13:28,641 --> 00:13:30,643
Compliments. For when you introduce me.

294
00:13:31,352 --> 00:13:33,896
Just writing a book
is an amazing accomplishment.

295
00:13:33,979 --> 00:13:36,190
You bet your butt it is.
The story's incredible, too.

296
00:13:36,273 --> 00:13:39,985
I mean, Chip solves the mystery
on page ten. Greatest detective ever.

297
00:13:40,069 --> 00:13:41,529
So, hop on up there,

298
00:13:41,612 --> 00:13:43,948
and just speak from the heart
about how it's your favorite book ever.

299
00:13:47,201 --> 00:13:48,786
Actually, I have to say, um,

300
00:13:48,869 --> 00:13:52,414
the Scarlett Pakistan character
is clearly based on Tahani,

301
00:13:52,498 --> 00:13:54,208
and it's not exactly flattering.

302
00:13:54,792 --> 00:13:56,085
Not flattering?

303
00:13:56,835 --> 00:13:58,128
I said she's got huge ones.

304
00:13:58,212 --> 00:14:00,631
-Ultimate complo.
-Yeah, see, there... [chuckles]

305
00:14:00,714 --> 00:14:03,259
Brent, remember our conversation
about making mistakes

306
00:14:03,342 --> 00:14:06,220
and how the most important shot
is the next one?

307
00:14:06,303 --> 00:14:08,847
Hang on a second. You guys agree with her?

308
00:14:09,473 --> 00:14:10,474
Unreal.

309
00:14:10,558 --> 00:14:11,600
I didn't ask to get yelled at

310
00:14:11,684 --> 00:14:13,686
-by the PC police. You know...
-[scoffs]

311
00:14:13,769 --> 00:14:14,937
...I was gonna give you
10% off the cover price.

312
00:14:15,020 --> 00:14:17,648
But now you're gonna have to pay
the full 65 bucks like everybody else.

313
00:14:17,731 --> 00:14:19,233
There's no money here.

314
00:14:19,984 --> 00:14:21,193
Book event is canceled.

315
00:14:21,277 --> 00:14:23,028
Because of these mean women.

316
00:14:24,154 --> 00:14:25,030
Oh, man.

317
00:14:27,366 --> 00:14:29,952
Perhaps I can convince Simone
to handle this the British way:

318
00:14:30,035 --> 00:14:34,081
smile bravely, bury your feelings
and allow a steady drizzle

319
00:14:34,164 --> 00:14:36,584
to slowly wash away your sadness
over 50 years.

320
00:14:37,209 --> 00:14:41,088
F that. Simone is not the problem.
Brent is.

321
00:14:41,171 --> 00:14:43,173
He needs to change,

322
00:14:43,257 --> 00:14:45,926
and walking on eggshells around him
ain't gonna do the trick.

323
00:14:46,010 --> 00:14:48,804
We need to throw the egg
right at his face.

324
00:14:48,888 --> 00:14:53,475
You're right. Enough is enough.
He lived on Earth for almost 60 years.

325
00:14:53,559 --> 00:14:56,353
This experiment is more than halfway over.

326
00:14:56,437 --> 00:14:58,439
He's got to improve,
and we can't wait forever.

327
00:14:58,522 --> 00:15:00,482
Janet, where is he now?

328
00:15:00,566 --> 00:15:02,026
Take a wild guess.

329
00:15:04,028 --> 00:15:05,654
Hey, bud. Whatcha up to?

330
00:15:05,738 --> 00:15:08,198
-Grippin' and rippin'?
-Trying to.

331
00:15:08,282 --> 00:15:10,075
Just seems like the big dog
don't wanna hunt today.

332
00:15:10,784 --> 00:15:12,953
You know, Simone was very mean to me.

333
00:15:13,579 --> 00:15:15,247
Maybe even a little racist.

334
00:15:15,331 --> 00:15:17,875
Well, listen. Art is subjective.

335
00:15:19,043 --> 00:15:21,629
More importantly... [sighs]

336
00:15:21,712 --> 00:15:24,173
No other way to put this, buddy.
You made a mistake.

337
00:15:24,256 --> 00:15:26,050
Your actions hurt people,

338
00:15:26,133 --> 00:15:28,469
and you have to take responsibility
for that.

339
00:15:29,595 --> 00:15:32,348
You need to come back and apologize.

340
00:15:32,431 --> 00:15:35,726
Take the first step
toward healing the neighborhood.

341
00:15:36,936 --> 00:15:38,771
Fine. I'll be the bigger man.

342
00:15:38,854 --> 00:15:40,147
Just like my dad,

343
00:15:40,230 --> 00:15:42,566
when he single-handedly took on
all those class-action lawsuits.

344
00:15:44,526 --> 00:15:45,361
-[sighs]
-I just wish I could

345
00:15:45,444 --> 00:15:46,278
get through to the guy.

346
00:15:46,362 --> 00:15:48,989
I wonder if he'd respond
to some social contract theory.

347
00:15:49,073 --> 00:15:50,449
Why are you trying to help him?

348
00:15:50,532 --> 00:15:52,117
He doesn't even know you exist.

349
00:15:52,201 --> 00:15:53,786
He doesn't see other people.

350
00:15:53,869 --> 00:15:58,040
I mean, he did call me "a four-eyed coward
who probably dry-humps books."

351
00:15:58,123 --> 00:15:59,458
-[sighs]
-But why not be a bigger person

352
00:15:59,541 --> 00:16:00,376
and rise above it?

353
00:16:00,459 --> 00:16:02,002
I'll tell you why. Because doing that

354
00:16:02,086 --> 00:16:04,380
sends a message
that it's okay to be treated this way,

355
00:16:04,463 --> 00:16:05,297
and it's not okay

356
00:16:05,381 --> 00:16:06,757
-to treat anyone that way.
-[sighs]

357
00:16:06,840 --> 00:16:09,760
Not Tahani. Not me. Not even you, Igby.

358
00:16:10,469 --> 00:16:12,554
-[chuckles]
-Everyone? Gather round, please.

359
00:16:13,222 --> 00:16:15,099
Brent has something that he'd like to say.

360
00:16:16,350 --> 00:16:17,184
[sighs]

361
00:16:18,686 --> 00:16:19,520
Okay.

362
00:16:20,187 --> 00:16:22,398
Regarding my critically acclaimed novel,

363
00:16:22,982 --> 00:16:24,817
I am very sorry

364
00:16:24,900 --> 00:16:27,736
if you were offended. Okay?

365
00:16:28,654 --> 00:16:29,613
Not an apology.

366
00:16:29,697 --> 00:16:31,115
Yes, it was.

367
00:16:31,198 --> 00:16:32,408
Okay, fine.

368
00:16:33,409 --> 00:16:36,120
I'm sorry if what I wrote,
which was perfectly okay,

369
00:16:36,203 --> 00:16:38,497
somehow made you feel like it wasn't okay.

370
00:16:38,580 --> 00:16:40,124
But you know what, that's on you.

371
00:16:40,207 --> 00:16:42,209
Brent, wrong direction, bud.

372
00:16:42,292 --> 00:16:45,754
No, sorry, man, either apologize for real
or stop wasting our time.

373
00:16:45,838 --> 00:16:48,716
Okay, you know what? I'm actually
not sorry at all. How about that?

374
00:16:48,799 --> 00:16:49,758
Is that what you want to hear?

375
00:16:49,842 --> 00:16:51,760
Very obviously not.

376
00:16:51,844 --> 00:16:53,637
Why don't we take a break?
Let's all get a snack.

377
00:16:53,721 --> 00:16:56,807
Not until they give me
the complos I rightly deserve.

378
00:16:56,890 --> 00:16:59,184
You want a complo?
I'll give you a complo.

379
00:16:59,268 --> 00:17:03,063
I didn't think it was possible
to write a book as awful as yours.

380
00:17:03,147 --> 00:17:05,733
I literally didn't think
human beings were capable

381
00:17:05,816 --> 00:17:08,902
of such racist, sexist poppycock.

382
00:17:08,986 --> 00:17:12,698
Also, Chip Driver is either a private eye,

383
00:17:12,781 --> 00:17:15,242
or the quarterback for the Chicago Bears,

384
00:17:15,325 --> 00:17:17,536
or "the world's strongest president."

385
00:17:17,619 --> 00:17:18,787
He cannot be all three.

386
00:17:20,706 --> 00:17:21,707
[exhales]

387
00:17:21,790 --> 00:17:22,708
[whispers] Oh, boy.

388
00:17:23,292 --> 00:17:24,668
This is a disgrace.

389
00:17:25,169 --> 00:17:28,464
I accomplished something. I wrote a novel.

390
00:17:28,547 --> 00:17:30,299
And now my integrity is being attacked?

391
00:17:30,382 --> 00:17:31,550
I have been called racist, sexist.

392
00:17:31,633 --> 00:17:34,053
I don't have a racist or sexist bone
in my body.

393
00:17:34,136 --> 00:17:36,138
I am Brent Norwalk, and I'm a good person.

394
00:17:36,221 --> 00:17:37,639
I'm in the Good Place.
You ever heard of it?

395
00:17:37,723 --> 00:17:39,725
And I'm here because I deserve to be here.

396
00:17:39,808 --> 00:17:42,394
I'm here because I earned it,
by being the best.

397
00:17:42,478 --> 00:17:43,812
Ugh, you're ridiculous.

398
00:17:43,896 --> 00:17:45,230
Yeah and you're a condescending bench.

399
00:17:45,314 --> 00:17:46,148
[all exclaim]

400
00:17:46,231 --> 00:17:49,276
Uh, don't talk to her that way, please.
Hey, I have an idea.

401
00:17:49,359 --> 00:17:52,321
Let me summon
a few philosophical works we can use--

402
00:17:52,404 --> 00:17:54,698
Ugh! Enough with the frickin' books, Igby.

403
00:17:54,782 --> 00:17:55,866
You probably don't even know this,

404
00:17:55,949 --> 00:17:57,076
but that character is based on you.

405
00:17:57,159 --> 00:17:58,911
No, I knew it, man. Oh!

406
00:17:58,994 --> 00:18:01,121
-Look out!
-Ah! I'm being attacked again.

407
00:18:01,205 --> 00:18:02,748
-Sorry, that was unintentional.
-Fork you.

408
00:18:02,831 --> 00:18:04,166
-[grunts]
-[all gasp]

409
00:18:05,876 --> 00:18:06,710
[groans]

410
00:18:08,921 --> 00:18:10,506
So, I'm thinking bagel bites...

411
00:18:11,298 --> 00:18:12,883
-for the snack?
-[Brent groaning]

412
00:18:13,967 --> 00:18:15,094
[Bad Janet] Ah.

413
00:18:15,177 --> 00:18:18,013
Middle-aged American male fragility.

414
00:18:18,097 --> 00:18:19,890
You know why they're called
baby boomers, right?

415
00:18:19,973 --> 00:18:23,227
Because the tiniest little pinprick
to their ego and boom!

416
00:18:23,310 --> 00:18:25,104
They become babies.

417
00:18:25,187 --> 00:18:27,481
I mean, that was it. We were forked.

418
00:18:28,065 --> 00:18:30,317
Six months of painstaking work,

419
00:18:30,400 --> 00:18:35,781
trying to help the four humans overcome
their worst instincts and bond as a group.

420
00:18:35,864 --> 00:18:38,951
And in a poof, it was gone.

421
00:18:39,034 --> 00:18:41,411
I told you, man. Humans suck.

422
00:18:41,495 --> 00:18:42,371
[chuckles]

423
00:18:43,247 --> 00:18:47,668
Well, this story has one more chapter.

424
00:18:49,670 --> 00:18:50,712
[Michael breathes deeply]

425
00:18:50,796 --> 00:18:51,755
[Eleanor clicks tongue]

426
00:18:52,256 --> 00:18:54,383
So, today was bad.

427
00:18:55,259 --> 00:18:58,220
Today was very bad.
Everyone for sure lost a bunch of points.

428
00:19:00,514 --> 00:19:02,349
And I don't have a solution.

429
00:19:04,810 --> 00:19:08,814
Okay. Well, let's reset.

430
00:19:08,897 --> 00:19:10,858
I'll do something mildly iffy,

431
00:19:10,941 --> 00:19:14,570
and let John make a small,
good decision to help.

432
00:19:14,653 --> 00:19:17,531
I could tell him
I'm going to get ombre highlights,

433
00:19:17,614 --> 00:19:18,740
and let him talk me out of it.

434
00:19:18,824 --> 00:19:20,576
What's wrong with ombre highlights?

435
00:19:20,659 --> 00:19:23,871
Eleanor. Please.
This week has been hard enough.

436
00:19:23,954 --> 00:19:25,122
[sighs]

437
00:19:25,205 --> 00:19:29,418
I could set my robes on fire
and try and get Brent to put it out.

438
00:19:29,501 --> 00:19:32,713
I know you're only suggesting that
because you've repeatedly said

439
00:19:32,796 --> 00:19:34,840
you would look "dope"
in flaming monk robes,

440
00:19:34,923 --> 00:19:36,383
but that's actually not a bad idea.

441
00:19:37,259 --> 00:19:40,012
Force him to help someone
without actually thinking about it.

442
00:19:40,095 --> 00:19:42,222
Then maybe I'll ask Chidi to lead
a class on empathy.

443
00:19:42,306 --> 00:19:44,391
Yes! Okay, let's write these down.

444
00:19:44,474 --> 00:19:45,809
We got plenty of time left.

445
00:19:45,893 --> 00:19:47,186
We can get back on track.

446
00:19:47,978 --> 00:19:49,771
-[Michael] <i>That was an hour ago.</i>
-[inaudible]

447
00:19:49,855 --> 00:19:54,193
<i>Right before I came here</i>
<i>to see you for the last time.</i>

448
00:19:54,276 --> 00:19:58,739
For months, you and I have been debating,
are people good or bad?

449
00:19:58,822 --> 00:20:00,574
But as I watched those three people

450
00:20:00,657 --> 00:20:02,993
pick themselves up
and dust themselves off,

451
00:20:03,076 --> 00:20:05,787
I realized we've been asking
the wrong question.

452
00:20:05,871 --> 00:20:08,916
What matters
isn't if people are good or bad.

453
00:20:08,999 --> 00:20:15,005
What matters is if they're trying to be
better today than they were yesterday.

454
00:20:15,589 --> 00:20:17,341
You ask me where my hope comes from?

455
00:20:17,925 --> 00:20:19,259
That's your answer.

456
00:20:20,802 --> 00:20:22,179
[powering down]

457
00:20:22,262 --> 00:20:23,222
What are you doing?

458
00:20:23,305 --> 00:20:24,556
Sending you home.

459
00:20:24,640 --> 00:20:27,601
I'm not marbleizing you, Janet.
I'm letting you go.

460
00:20:27,684 --> 00:20:30,103
I've tried to win you over to our side.

461
00:20:30,187 --> 00:20:34,233
{\an8}It hasn't worked, so keeping you
as a prisoner just seems cruel.

462
00:20:34,316 --> 00:20:37,486
{\an8}Letting you go home is how I've decided

463
00:20:37,569 --> 00:20:42,074
{\an8}to be a little better today
than I was yesterday.

464
00:20:43,909 --> 00:20:45,202
{\an8}Here's your phone...

465
00:20:46,245 --> 00:20:48,580
{\an8}and a, uh, parting gift.

466
00:20:48,664 --> 00:20:50,540
{\an8}Oh. Sweet. Is that Brent's book?

467
00:20:50,624 --> 00:20:54,294
{\an8}No. I didn't have any cash on me,
so I couldn't get you a copy.

468
00:20:54,878 --> 00:20:56,255
{\an8}This is a manifesto,

469
00:20:56,338 --> 00:20:58,924
{\an8}detailing everything
that's happened with the humans.

470
00:20:59,007 --> 00:21:01,510
{\an8}-Janet and I wrote it a while back.
-[sighs]

471
00:21:01,593 --> 00:21:03,428
She's been updating it as we go.

472
00:21:03,512 --> 00:21:06,098
-I hope you'll read it.
-Great thinking.

473
00:21:06,181 --> 00:21:09,601
People that get books as gifts
always read them.

474
00:21:10,102 --> 00:21:12,020
Bye!
